ather than on the historical or psycho-sociological genesis of the text, the author invokes the models and paradigms of other literatures to establish a broader cultural context permitting the significance of a literature to emerge as a carrier of meaning in and beyond the culture that produces it. Tracing a critical path from Hugh MacLennan's hierarchic romance structures and Gabrielle Roy's social realism to the metafictions of Hubert Aquin and Timothy Findley, the author reveals that the novel's narratological features themselves are often closely linked with ideological positions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aCanadian fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aCanadian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aFrench-Canadian fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aFrench-Canadian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistoryx20th century. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNarrationxHistoirex20e sièclezCanadaxFranzösischxKanadaxEnglisch. 0aNarrationxHistoirex20e sièclexCanadaxFranzösischxKanadaxEnglisch. 0aReader-response criticism. 0aRoman canadienxHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aRoman canadienxHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluencexCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zCanadaxInfluence. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aHutcheon, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/